// zig-zone tailnet ACL policy.
//
// Source of truth: this file. Paste into Tailscale admin → Access Controls
// when changed. The admin policy editor supports JSONC (comments).
//
// Identity model (Tailscale's, not invented here):
//   - `zig-computer` is tagged `tag:server` — machine identity, no human
//     user behind it. Lives on OVH (public-internet edge); the tag-based
//     isolation matters here because a compromise shouldn't grant
//     "act as the owner" rights.
//   - `pico` is UNTAGGED (owned by the tailnet owner). Originally tagged
//     `tag:server` until 2026-05-24 — flipped to user-owned to enable
//     native Taildrop with iPhone/metis (Tailscale hard-locks Taildrop
//     to same-user transfers; see runbook gotcha #23 + bead dotfiles-f7n).
//     pico is internal home-LAN compute; the tag-based isolation was a
//     weaker fit there (already behind the home router).
//   - `metis`, `iphone-15-pro` are UNTAGGED — they authenticate as the
//     user's Tailscale account, so they match `autogroup:member` (devices
//     owned by a human Tailscale account).
//   - `autogroup:member` is src-only in Tailscale ACLs; `autogroup:self`
//     is the correct dst for "user's own other devices."
//   - User identities (e.g. `azigler@github`) cannot be the dst when
//     src is a tag — Tailscale rejects with "users in dst are only
//     allowed from the same user." For tagged-server → user-owned
//     traffic, use a `hosts` block to alias the device by IP, then
//     reference the host name as dst. The `hosts` block below maps
//     `pico` → its tailnet IP; if pico ever re-registers and gets a
//     new IP, update that one line.
//
// Four rules cover the full traffic matrix:
//   1. server-to-server  (zig ↔ any future tagged servers)
//   2. user-to-server    (laptop/phone → zig over tailnet: SSH, ollama API)
//   3. user-to-self      (laptop ↔ phone ↔ pico over tailnet, incl Taildrop)
//   4. server-to-owner   (zig → pico-as-user-device: nginx proxy, etc.)
//
// Future contractor / co-owner devices not tied to the user's account
// match NO rule and are denied by default — allowlist-default-deny.
//
// SSH section: all rules `accept` — no Tailscale-identity re-auth required.
// Rationale: machine-to-machine automation (the granola webhook on pico
// pushes transcripts to zig-computer via ssh on every Zapier hit) cannot
// tolerate the 12h `check` re-auth expiry — when the check session lapsed
// the webhook would fail silently with no operator in the loop to click an
// auth URL. Removing `check` accepts that any compromised user-owned device
// can SSH into the user's own tailnet devices without browser re-verify;
// bounded because the attacker would already have full tailnet identity and
// could do anything else within the ACL anyway. Flipped from `check` →
// `accept` on 2026-05-26 (see commit message for context).
//
// Three SSH rules:
//   1. autogroup:member → tag:server — user-owned devices (metis, iPhone,
//      pico-as-untagged) SSH into tagged servers (zig-computer). Users:
//      `ubuntu` (Linux user on zig) or autogroup:nonroot (any non-root,
//      e.g. `pico` on the Mac). Action: `accept`.
//   2. autogroup:member → autogroup:self — user-owned devices SSH into
//      each other (metis → pico, etc.). Action: `accept`.
//   3. tag:server → tag:server — server-to-server SSH. Action: `accept`
//      (and structurally must be — Tailscale rejects `check` with
//      tag:server in src: "'check' action does not support tags in src").
//
// See spec bead `dotfiles-phe` § 4.2 for the rationale + § 6 OQs for
// decisions that shaped this. Server-to-server rule added post-spec as a
// real-world gap discovered during Phase 1 testing (bead dotfiles-qix).
//
// NOTE on Taildrop: it is HARD-LOCKED to same-user device-to-device
// transfers. There is NO ACL grant, nodeAttr, or admin toggle to enable
// it between tagged devices and user-owned devices (or between users).
// `tailscale file cp /tmp/foo iphone-15-pro:` from zig-computer (tagged)
// returns "cannot send files: peer is owned by a different user" by
// design — confirmed via Tailscale docs kb/1106/taildrop. An attempted
// `grants` block targeting `tailscale.com/cap/file-sharing` was rejected
// by the policy editor with "Error: capability name must not be in the
// tailscale.com domain" — the namespace is reserved for built-in,
// non-user-configurable features. See bead dotfiles-f7n (closed
// won't-fix) + zig-zone runbook gotcha #23 for the workarounds (HTTP
// over tailnet IP, SSH relay through a user-owned tailnet device, or
// untagging the source — none ideal).

{
  "tagOwners": {
    "tag:server": ["autogroup:admin"]
  },

  // Aliases: hostname → tailnet IP. Used as dst when we can't reference
  // by tag (because the device is user-owned) and can't reference by
  // user identity (Tailscale rejects user dst from tag src — and group
  // dst, per 2026-05-24 grammar test: "Error: groups are not allowed
  // dst"). The combination effectively means Tailscale SSH has NO
  // syntax for tag-src → user-owned-dst — see alt-port macOS sshd
  // pattern on pico (Port 2222 bypasses tailscaled's intercept).
  "hosts": {
    "pico": "100.72.47.4",
    "metis": "100.106.120.98"
  },

  "acls": [
    // 1. server-to-server (tag:server ↔ tag:server)
    {
      "action": "accept",
      "src": ["tag:server"],
      "dst": ["tag:server:*"]
    },
    // 2. user-to-server (user-owned devices reach tagged servers, e.g. SSH, ollama API)
    {
      "action": "accept",
      "src": ["autogroup:member"],
      "dst": ["tag:server:*"]
    },
    // 3. user-to-self (user's own devices talk to each other — incl. pico now)
    {
      "action": "accept",
      "src": ["autogroup:member"],
      "dst": ["autogroup:self:*"]
    },
    // 4. server-to-pico (zig-computer reaches pico for nginx proxying
    // vs14-web, ollama API queries, etc.). After pico was untagged
    // (2026-05-24), it can't be referenced by tag, and Tailscale doesn't
    // allow user identities as dst from tag src ("users in dst are only
    // allowed from the same user"). The host alias above keeps the
    // reference stable.
    {
      "action": "accept",
      "src": ["tag:server"],
      "dst": ["pico:*"]
    },
    // 5. server-to-metis (zig-computer SSHes to metis to run the
    // zettelkasten backup script before the andrewzigler.com build pulls
    // from github.com/azigler/zettelkasten). metis is user-owned/untagged,
    // so — like pico (rule 4) — it can't be a tag dst and is referenced via
    // the hosts alias. Port 22 only (least privilege). metis runs native
    // macOS OpenSSH (the GUI Tailscale build has no Tailscale-SSH server,
    // so tailscaled does not intercept :22) — plain key-auth SSH works, no
    // alt-port needed. Added 2026-06-21 (build: trigger metis zk-backup).
    {
      "action": "accept",
      "src": ["tag:server"],
      "dst": ["metis:22"]
    }
  ],

  "ssh": [
    {
      "action": "accept",
      "src":    ["autogroup:member"],
      "dst":    ["tag:server"],
      "users":  ["ubuntu", "autogroup:nonroot"],
      // acceptEnv: Tailscale SSH doesn't passthrough env vars by default
      // (unlike OpenBSD sshd). Without this, TERM + LANG + LC_* from the
      // client are stripped, the remote shell falls back to POSIX locale,
      // and Unicode/nerdfont glyph rendering breaks. Especially visible
      // on iPhone Termius (bead dotfiles-st2). Requires Tailscale ≥ 1.76.
      "acceptEnv": ["TERM", "LANG", "LC_*"]
    },
    {
      // user-to-self SSH (e.g. metis → pico now that pico is user-owned).
      "action": "accept",
      "src":    ["autogroup:member"],
      "dst":    ["autogroup:self"],
      "users":  ["autogroup:nonroot"],
      "acceptEnv": ["TERM", "LANG", "LC_*"]
    },
    {
      "action": "accept",
      "src":    ["tag:server"],
      "dst":    ["tag:server"],
      "users":  ["autogroup:nonroot"],
      "acceptEnv": ["TERM", "LANG", "LC_*"]
    },
    // INTENTIONALLY NO zig→pico Tailscale SSH rule. Tailscale's SSH
    // grammar has NO valid dst expression for "tag-src → user-owned-dst":
    //   - user identity dst: rejected ("users in dst are only allowed
    //     from the same user")
    //   - group dst containing user identity: rejected ("groups are not
    //     allowed dst")
    //   - host alias dst: rejected (SSH dst is identity-class only)
    //   - autogroup:self: only valid when src is a user, not a tag
    // Workaround: macOS sshd on pico listens on Port 2222 in addition
    // to Port 22. Port 22 stays owned by tailscaled (Tailscale SSH for
    // iPhone/metis). Port 2222 falls through directly to macOS sshd,
    // bypassed by tailscaled's port-22 intercept. zig-computer's
    // ~/.ssh/local has `Host pico Port 2222` so `ssh pico` works
    // transparently via key auth.
  ]
}
